"""
Task 25: Add 50 new questions to seed_questions.json
"""
import json

new_qs = [
  {"id":"tp-021","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"k-factor tables","difficulty":"medium","question":"Using AS/NZS 3000 Table 3, a cable run of 0.8km carrying 15A in conduit on a concrete slab uses a k-factor of 11.7. The voltage drop is:","options":["14.04V","7.02V","28.08V","3.51V"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — V = k × I × L = 11.7 × 15 × 0.8 = 140.4 ÷ 10 (100m unit) = 14.04V. For a 230V general circuit, 14.04V is within the 7% limit (16.1V). Option B (7.02V) would result from using 0.4km. Option C (28.08V) requires a 2km run. Option D (3.51V) is dividing by 40 instead of 10 in the unit conversion.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.6; Table 3"},
  {"id":"tp-022","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Conductor sizing interaction","difficulty":"hard","question":"A 40m run of 4mm² copper conductor in conduit carries 20A and drops 6.2V. To limit voltage drop to 9.2V for this circuit, the minimum conductor size required is:","options":["6mm² copper","4mm² is sufficient","10mm² copper","2.5mm² copper"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — At 40m with 20A load, 4mm² drops 6.2V. To achieve ≤9.2V, the current-carrying capacity must be checked and if the existing conductor passes ampacity but fails volt-drop, the next standard size up (6mm²) must be selected. AS/NZS 3000 Clauses 3.2 and 3.6 require both ampacity AND voltage drop to be satisfied — where volt-drop governs, the larger conductor is mandatory. Option B fails because the question explicitly asks what is needed to meet the 9.2V limit. Option D (2.5mm²) would be worse.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clauses 3.2, 3.6; AS/NZS 3008"},
  {"id":"tp-023","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Multicore cable grouping","difficulty":"medium","question":"Three identical 230V single-phase sub-circuits share a common conduit. Each carries 10A. When calculating voltage drop for the worst-case circuit, the correct approach is:","options":["Each circuit is calculated individually using its own current and length — grouping affects ampacity via AS/NZS 3008 but not voltage drop calculation","The combined heating from all three circuits must be added to the voltage drop calculation","All three circuit currents add vectorially to 30A for voltage drop purposes","Grouped circuits receive a 50% voltage drop reduction factor"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3008 voltage drop calculations are per-circuit, per-current, per-length. The grouping factor for current-carrying capacity (AS/NZS 3008 Table 2) does NOT change the individual circuit voltage drop calculation. Each circuit's voltage drop is calculated using its own current and resistance — the fact that cables are in the same conduit is already implicitly accounted for in the k-factor. Option B — grouping affects ampacity (heating), not voltage drop. Option C — this is incorrect. Option D — no such voltage drop grouping factor exists in AS/NZS 3000.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.6; AS/NZS 3008 Tables 1-30"},
  {"id":"tp-024","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Three-phase voltage drop","difficulty":"medium","question":"A three-phase motor circuit operates at 400V line-to-line, runs 100m, and carries 26A per phase. Using AS/NZS 3000 Clause 3.6 three-phase voltage drop formula (V = √3 × k × I × L / 1000) with k=1.8 for the selected cable, the voltage drop is closest to:","options":["8.1V","4.7V","14.0V","2.4V"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — V = √3 × k × I × L / 1000 = 1.732 × 1.8 × 26 × 100 / 1000 = 1.732 × 1.8 × 2.6 = 1.732 × 4.68 = 8.10V. This is within the 7% voltage drop limit for a general motor circuit (400V × 0.07 = 28V). Option B (4.7V) would be using 0.5km instead of 0.1km. Option C (14V) would require k=3.1 which is for a different installation method.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.6; AS/NZS 3008"},
  {"id":"tp-025","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Voltage drop limit determination","difficulty":"medium","question":"A 230V sub-main supplying a distribution board that feeds both lighting and general power circuits has a maximum permissible voltage drop of:","options":["7% (16.1V) — sub-mains supplying mixed loads use the general circuit limit per Clause 3.6.2(b)","5% (11.5V) — the strictest limit applies throughout the installation","3% (6.9V) — sub-mains are held to a tighter standard","9% (20.7V) — sub-mains are permitted a higher drop than final circuits"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 3.6.2 distinguishes: lighting circuits (5% limit) vs general circuits (7% limit). A sub-main that feeds both lighting and power is classified as a general-use circuit — 7% limit applies. The strictest limit in a mixed board is 5% (for the lighting portion) but the sub-main itself is assessed at 7% because it is not exclusively a lighting circuit. Option B applies only to dedicated lighting sub-mains. Option C is not a standard limit. Option D — sub-mains do not get a higher limit than final circuits.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.6.2"},
  {"id":"tp-026","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Voltage drop vs ampacity","difficulty":"hard","question":"When voltage drop calculations require a larger conductor than current-carrying capacity calculations, the installation designer must:","options":["Select the larger conductor size determined by voltage drop — both requirements must be satisfied","Always use the ampacity-derived size and document the voltage drop deviation","Apply to the supply authority for a voltage variation approval","Use voltage-drop size only for lighting, ampacity size for power circuits"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 3.2 is explicit: conductor size must satisfy BOTH current-carrying capacity AND voltage drop requirements. Where voltage drop requires a larger conductor, the larger size is mandatory. This is not optional and does not require supply authority approval for normal installations — the designer simply selects the larger conductor. Option B is non-compliant — voltage drop is a mandatory requirement. Option C is only applicable in exceptional circumstances where supply authority voltage variation is agreed. Option D is arbitrary and not supported by the standard.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clauses 3.2, 3.6"},
  {"id":"tp-027","topic":"Voltage Drop","sub_topic":"Voltage drop proportionality","difficulty":"medium","question":"Voltage drop in a conductor is proportional to which combination of factors?","options":["Current flowing and conductor resistance (which increases with length and decreases with larger cross-section)","Supply voltage and frequency","Ambient temperature and installation method only","Power factor and reactive impedance only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Ohm's Law for a conductor: V = I × R. Resistance R = ρ × L / A. So V_drop increases with higher current and longer length, and decreases with larger conductor area. Option B — supply voltage determines the percentage limit context, not the magnitude of V_drop in the formula. Frequency has no effect on resistive volt-drop in this context. Option C — ambient temperature affects ampacity but not directly the volt-drop formula (though temperature slightly increases R). Option D — for purely resistive circuits at 50Hz, PF has no effect; for circuits with significant reactance, PF affects reactive volt-drop component, but AS/NZS 3000's simplified volt-drop method using k-factors accounts for this.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.6"},
  {"id":"tp-028","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"Zs measurement procedure","difficulty":"medium","question":"When measuring Zs (earth fault loop impedance) at a socket outlet, the correct procedure is:","options":["Measure between the phase conductor and the earth contact at the outlet with the circuit energised and the earthing system connected","Isolate the circuit, disconnect the earthing conductor, and measure phase to the disconnected earth rod","Measure between neutral and earth at the outlet","Zs can only be calculated, not measured, on an operational installation"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Zs is measured with the installation energised and earthing fully connected. The instrument measures between line and earth at the outlet — this gives Zs = Ze + Zt (total loop). AS/NZS 3019 specifies the method: a high-current test pulse (15-20A) is injected between line and earth and the resulting voltage drop is measured. Option B is wrong — disconnecting earthing breaks the loop, giving an open-circuit reading, not Zs. Option C gives the neutral-earth voltage which indicates neutral integrity issues, not loop impedance. Option D is false — Zs is routinely measured in-service with a loop impedance tester.","reference":"AS/NZS 3019; AS/NZS 3000 Clause 5.3"},
  {"id":"tp-029","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"Ze responsibility","difficulty":"medium","question":"Ze (external earth fault loop impedance) is primarily the responsibility of:","options":["The supply network operator — it is measured at the point of supply and is outside the electrician's scope","The installing electrician who designed the installation","The property owner","The meter service provider"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Ze is the external loop impedance from the supply transformer to the point of supply. The supply authority is responsible for maintaining Ze at a level that allows the installation's protective devices to operate within AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1 limits when combined with the installation's internal Zt. The electrician's responsibility is Zt (internal loop impedance within the installation). Ze is declared by the supply authority and can be measured at the point of supply. Option B — electrician is responsible for Zt, not Ze. Option C — property owners have no responsibility for supply network characteristics. Option D — meter providers deal with metering, not supply earthing.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2; NZ Electrical Regulations"},
  {"id":"tp-030","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"Zs compliance","difficulty":"hard","question":"A Type B 16A MCB protects a socket outlet circuit. AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1 specifies maximum Zs of 1.83Ω. A measured Zs of 1.90Ω at the furthest socket means:","options":["Non-compliant — Zs must not exceed the Table 5.1 value under any circumstances","Compliant because the MCB would eventually clear the fault","Non-compliant but acceptable if Ze is subtracted from the measured Zs","Compliant because the fault current is still sufficient to operate the MCB"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 5.3 is absolute: Zs shall NOT EXCEED the Table 5.1 value. 1.90Ω > 1.83Ω = non-compliant. The Zs limit exists to ensure: (1) sufficient fault current flows for the protective device to operate within the required time; (2) touch voltages during the fault remain below safe limits. Option B is wrong — compliance is determined by the absolute Zs limit, not by whether the device would eventually trip. Option C is a dangerous and non-compliant practice — Ze cannot be subtracted from a measured Zs. Option D is the same error as B.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.3; Table 5.1"},
  {"id":"tp-031","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"Zt calculation","difficulty":"hard","question":"The resistance of 50m of 2.5mm² copper phase conductor at 20°C is 0.694Ω. The earth continuity conductor in the same run is 1.5mm² with resistance 1.15Ω. The Zt contribution from this cable run is:","options":["1.84Ω (phase 0.694Ω + earth 1.15Ω, summed for the line-to-earth fault path)","0.694Ω only — the earth path resistance is not included in Zt for a line-to-earth fault","2.31Ω (direct sum of phase and earth resistance)","Zt cannot be calculated without knowing the actual route length of the earth conductor"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — For a line-to-earth fault, the fault current path is: line conductor (origin → fault) + earth continuity conductor (fault → origin MET). The total loop resistance is Rline + Rearth. 50m of 2.5mm² copper = 0.694Ω (phase). 50m of 1.5mm² copper = 1.15Ω (earth CPC). Zt = 0.694 + 1.15 = 1.844Ω. Option B is wrong — Zt includes the earth return path. Option C is wrong — while the correct answer is numerically close to this, the correct concept is that both path segments must be summed. Option D is wrong — the route length of the earth is the same as the phase for a single cable run.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2; AS/NZS 3008"},
  {"id":"tp-032","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"Prospective fault current","difficulty":"medium","question":"Prospective fault current (PFC) at a main switchboard is measured at 3.2kA. The main switch is rated at 5kA. This installation:","options":["Is acceptable — the switch rating exceeds the maximum available fault current with adequate margin","Fails — the PFC exceeds the switch rating","Is borderline — a 40% derating factor must be applied","Is only acceptable if the PFC decreases below 2.5kA"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Protective devices must have an interrupting capacity (Icu/Icn) not less than the prospective fault current at the point of installation. A 5kA-rated device at a location where PFC = 3.2kA provides a 1.56× margin — well above the minimum requirements. Option B is wrong because 3.2kA < 5kA. Option C is wrong — no 40% derating is required when the device rating exceeds PFC. Option D is wrong — there is no such rule.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.6; AS/NZS 60898.1"},
  {"id":"tp-033","topic":"Fault Loop Impedance","sub_topic":"MCB type and Zs","difficulty":"hard","question":"AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1 gives different Zs limits for Type B, C, and D MCBs of the same current rating because:","options":["Type B devices have lower magnetic trip thresholds (3-5× In) requiring lower Zs for reliable operation within the required disconnection time","Type C devices are more sensitive and need higher Zs limits","Table 5.1 only applies to Type B devices","The difference is due to thermal overload characteristics only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Type B MCBs trip magnetically at 3-5× In, Type C at 5-10× In, Type D at 10-20× In. Because the magnetic trip threshold differs, the same Zs produces different fault currents and thus different tripping times. A Type B device needs a lower Zs to ensure the fault current (Zs/table_max) produces sufficient magnetic force to trip within 0.4s for final circuits. Type C and D tolerate higher Zs because their higher thresholds still produce enough magnetic force at the same Zs. Option B is wrong — Type C doesn't need higher Zs, it tolerates it. Option C is false. Option D is wrong — the difference is magnetic (instantaneous), not thermal.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 5.1; AS/NZS 60898.1"},
  {"id":"tp-034","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"Standard voltage scope","difficulty":"medium","question":"AS/NZS 3000 applies to electrical installations operating at which maximum voltage?","options":["1000V AC or 1500V DC (low voltage) — covering domestic through to light industrial","Any voltage above extra-low voltage (ELV)","33,000V — the limit for distribution networks","230V/400V only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 applies to low voltage, defined as not exceeding 1000V AC or 1500V DC between conductors, or 600V AC or 900V DC between a conductor and earth. This covers 230V single-phase domestic through 400V three-phase commercial/industrial. Option B — ELV is up to 50V AC or 120V DC; AS/NZS 3000 covers low voltage, not ELV. Option C — 33kV is distribution voltage, above low voltage. Option D is false — the standard explicitly covers up to 1000V AC.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 1.4"},
  {"id":"tp-035","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"Conductor identification","difficulty":"medium","question":"Per current NZ standards (AS/NZS 3000:2018 harmonised colour system), the colour coding for a neutral conductor in fixed wiring is:","options":["Blue (light blue) — harmonised international standard adopted in AS/NZS 3000:2018 for new work","Black — the old NZ convention (pre-2018)","Red — always the active/live conductor colour","Green/Yellow — for neutral in fixed wiring"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000:2018 adopted the international harmonised colour scheme (IEC 60446): Brown = line, Blue = neutral, Green/Yellow = earth for new work. For existing installations (pre-2018) using the old NZ colours, Black = neutral and Red = active were used. The current standard applies Blue for neutral in fixed wiring. Option B is the old NZ convention. Option C is the old NZ active colour. Option D — Green/Yellow is always earth/protective conductor, never neutral.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.8; Table 3"},
  {"id":"tp-036","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"Documentation requirements","difficulty":"medium","question":"AS/NZS 3000 and NZ Electricity (Safety) Regulations require which documentation for a completed electrical installation?","options":["A Certificate of Compliance (CoC) or Electrical Works Certificate issued by the licensed electrical worker, plus circuit schedules where applicable","A visual inspection report only","A manufacturer warranty card for all installed equipment","A load forecast for the next 10 years"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The Electricity (Safety) Regulations 2010 (NZ) and AS/NZS 3000 require a Certificate of Compliance (CoC) or Electrical Works Certificate to be issued by the licensed electrical worker for all notifiable work. Circuit schedules (legends/charts identifying each circuit and protective device) are also required where circuits have been installed or altered. Option B is insufficient. Option C is a product warranty matter, not a compliance requirement. Option D is a design document, not a regulatory requirement.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 1.6; Electricity (Safety) Regulations 2010 (NZ)"},
  {"id":"tp-037","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"MEN system","difficulty":"hard","question":"A Multiple Earthed Neutral (MEN) link is required in which type of earthing system in NZ?","options":["TN-C-S — where the supply PEN conductor is split at the installation origin into separate N and PE conductors connected by the MEN link","TT system only — where the installation earth electrode is completely isolated from the supply","IT system — high impedance earthed neutral","DC systems only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — MEN is the NZ term for TN-C-S. The supply provides a PEN (combined neutral-earth) conductor from the transformer. At the installation's origin, the PEN is 'split' into N and PE, which are connected at the Main Earth Terminal via the MEN link. This is the standard NZ earthing arrangement per AS/NZS 3000 Clause 5.2.1. Option B — TT has no PEN conductor; each electrode is independent. NZ distribution networks are not TT. Option C — IT is used in hospitals/critical infrastructure, not standard NZ installations. Option D — MEN is an AC system requirement.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2.1; NZECP 34"},
  {"id":"tp-038","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"EWRB notification","difficulty":"medium","question":"A property owner with a valid NZ electrical licence may legally:","options":["Carry out notifiable work on their own property — but must still lodge EWRB notification before starting the work","Carry out any electrical work on any property without restriction","Only carry out non-notifiable work; licensed electricians must do all notifiable work","Notify EWRB after completing the work, not before"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The Electricity (Safety) Regulations 2010 (NZ) apply to all persons regardless of licence status. Notifiable work requires EWRB notification BEFORE commencement — this applies to ALL notifiable work, whether done by a property owner or licensed electrician. A licensed property owner CAN do notifiable work on their own property — but must still notify EWRB first. Option B is wrong — licence does not permit unrestricted work on any property. Option C is partially true (non-notifiable = no restriction; notifiable = licensed electrician required), but a licensed property owner IS a licensed electrician in this context. Option D — notification must be BEFORE work, not after.","reference":"Electricity (Safety) Regulations 2010 (NZ); EWRB guidelines"},
  {"id":"tp-039","topic":"AS/NZS 3000 Application","sub_topic":"Connection to supply","difficulty":"medium","question":"Before connecting an electrical installation to the supply network, which must be completed?","options":["All tests in AS/NZS 3000 Chapter 8 (insulation resistance, earth continuity, Zs, polarity, RCD operation) and a Certificate of Compliance issued","Visual inspection only — testing can be done after connection","Testing only of circuits above 32A rating","Only the main switch needs testing before energisation"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 8.1 and the Electricity (Safety) Regulations require ALL verification tests to be completed BEFORE connection to the supply. These include: insulation resistance (all circuits and complete installation), earth continuity of protective conductors, Zs at the furthest point of each circuit, polarity, RCD operation, and any other specified tests. A Certificate of Compliance must also be issued. Option B is dangerous and non-compliant. Option C — all circuits must be tested regardless of rating. Option D is inadequate — comprehensive testing of all circuits is required.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 8.1; Appendix C"},
  {"id":"tp-040","topic":"Insulation Resistance","sub_topic":"IR test on complete installation","difficulty":"medium","question":"When testing the insulation resistance of a complete low voltage installation with all circuits connected and main switch closed, AS/NZS 3000 Table 8.1 specifies a minimum acceptable reading of:","options":["1 MΩ — the minimum for each circuit and the complete installation tested with a 500V DC insulation tester","0.5 MΩ for the complete installation","2 MΩ for each individual circuit","100 kΩ if the installation is less than 12 months old"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Table 8.1 specifies 1 MΩ as the minimum insulation resistance for any circuit or complete installation when tested with a 500V DC insulation tester. This applies to the complete installation with all circuits connected and all accessories in place. Option B (0.5 MΩ) is sometimes cited for individual appliances in isolation, not for installations. Option C (2 MΩ) is a good result but above the minimum. Option D (100 kΩ) is dangerously low and would indicate a serious fault requiring immediate investigation.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 8.1; Clause 8.3.4"},
  {"id":"tp-041","topic":"Insulation Resistance","sub_topic":"Electronic equipment IR testing","difficulty":"hard","question":"When testing insulation resistance on a circuit containing electronic equipment (dimmers, electronic ballasts, VSDs), the correct approach is:","options":["Isolate or disconnect the electronic equipment before applying the 500V test voltage — it may be damaged or give false low readings","Test through the electronic equipment as it is part of the installation","Electronic equipment does not affect insulation resistance readings","Apply only 250V test voltage to all circuits regardless of voltage rating"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Electronic equipment contains semiconductors and capacitors that can be damaged by the 500V DC insulation test voltage, and capacitors can store charge giving false low readings. AS/NZS 3000 Appendix C notes that electronic equipment should be disconnected or isolated before IR testing. Where disconnection is impractical, equipment should be tested separately per manufacturer instructions. Option B — applying insulation test voltage across electronic equipment can destroy it. Option C is false. Option D — the test voltage requirement does not change; the equipment must be isolated.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Appendix C; equipment manufacturer instructions"},
  {"id":"tp-042","topic":"Insulation Resistance","sub_topic":"Humidity effects on IR","difficulty":"medium","question":"Insulation resistance readings taken in high humidity (above 80% RH) should be interpreted with caution because:","options":["Moisture creates leakage paths on insulation surfaces, giving artificially low readings that may improve significantly when dry","High humidity has no effect on insulation resistance","Humidity only affects readings above 500 MΩ","IR testers automatically temperature- and humidity-compensate"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Moisture on conductor insulation, in terminations, and inside equipment creates conductive leakage paths that artificially reduce measured insulation resistance. A reading of 2 MΩ on a humid day could read 20 MΩ+ when dry. AS/NZS 3000 does not specify minimum humidity for testing but industry guidance is to note conditions and interpret borderline results in context. Condensation inside enclosures can cause genuine faults. Option B is false. Option C is nonsense. Option D is false — IR testers do not automatically compensate.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Appendix C"},
  {"id":"tp-043","topic":"Insulation Resistance","sub_topic":"IR test voltage selection","difficulty":"medium","question":"A 230V lighting circuit and a 24V ELV circuit share the same conduit. The insulation resistance test on the 230V circuit should be conducted at:","options":["500V DC — the highest voltage circuit in the group determines the test voltage; the ELV circuit should be isolated first","24V — to avoid damaging the ELV circuit","250V DC — the average of the two voltages","Test voltage selection is not relevant for mixed-voltage conduit runs"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Table 8.1 requires the test voltage to be appropriate to the circuit's nominal voltage. For circuits operating above 50V and up to 500V, 500V DC is required. The ELV circuit in the same conduit must be isolated before testing the 230V circuit — the 500V test voltage could damage ELV equipment. Option B would give meaningless results for the 230V circuit. Option C has no basis in the standard. Option D is false — test voltage selection is critical and mandatory.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 8.1; Clause 8.3.4"},
  {"id":"tp-044","topic":"Maximum Demand","sub_topic":"Diversity application","difficulty":"hard","question":"AS/NZS 3000 Table 4.2 diversity factors are applied to:","options":["Groups of similar circuits or appliances — not to individual dedicated circuits with their own protective device rating","Every individual circuit regardless of its type or rating","Only residential loads, not commercial installations","The total connected load before circuit subdivision"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Table 4.2 diversity factors apply to GROUPS of similar circuits. Individual dedicated circuits at their protective device rating are taken at 100% — no diversity is applied to a dedicated cooktop circuit or hot water circuit. The diversity is applied to groups: e.g., 8 identical lighting circuits: first 2 at 100%, remaining at 50%. Option B is wrong — dedicated circuits at their device rating don't receive additional diversity. Option C is wrong — Table 4.2 applies to all installation types. Option D is wrong — diversity is applied after subdivision, to groups of similar loads.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 4.2; Clause 4.2"},
  {"id":"tp-045","topic":"Maximum Demand","sub_topic":"Hot water cylinder demand","difficulty":"medium","question":"A 3.0kW 230V storage hot water cylinder with a dedicated 16A circuit contributes to maximum demand at:","options":["16A — dedicated fixed storage water heaters above 1kW are taken at 100% of circuit rating; no diversity factor applies","10A applying a 60% diversity factor","13A using an 80% factor","The cylinder is excluded from maximum demand calculations"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Per AS/NZS 3000 Table 4.2, fixed storage water heaters above 1kW are assessed at their circuit protective device rating — 100% no diversity. The 3.0kW cylinder at 230V draws 13A but the circuit is protected at 16A; maximum demand = 16A. Table 4.2 does not apply diversity to dedicated storage water heater circuits. Option B and C — these factors are not specified in Table 4.2 for storage water heaters. Option D is wrong — water heaters are significant loads and must be included.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 4.2; Clause 4.2"},
  {"id":"tp-046","topic":"Maximum Demand","sub_topic":"Lighting diversity calculation","difficulty":"medium","question":"A domestic installation has 8 identical 5A lighting circuits. Per AS/NZS 3000 Table 4.2, the maximum demand contribution of all 8 circuits is:","options":["25A — first 2 circuits at 100% (10A) plus remaining 6 at 50% (15A) = 25A","40A — all circuits at 100% with no diversity","10A — applying 50% diversity to all circuits","20A — a simplified calculation"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Table 4.2: first 2 circuits at 100%, subsequent at 50%. 8 × 5A circuits: (2 × 5A × 100%) + (6 × 5A × 50%) = 10A + 15A = 25A. Option B gives no diversity credit (wrong). Option C applies 50% to all including the first two (wrong). Option D (20A) is not the correct application of Table 4.2 for 8 circuits. Note: if the total connected load is used instead, different figures result — the standard's method is 25A.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 4.2"},
  {"id":"tp-047","topic":"Maximum Demand","sub_topic":"Motor load demand","difficulty":"hard","question":"For maximum demand calculation, a 7.5kW three-phase motor with FLC of 20A should be assessed at:","options":["20A at 100% — motor circuits are assessed at full load current for MD; starting current is a transient not used in MD calculations","20A × 125% = 25A to account for DOL starting","20A × 80% = 16A using a commercial diversity factor","Motor loads are excluded from MD calculations"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Motor circuits are assessed at 100% of full load current for maximum demand. Starting current (5-7× FLA for DOL) is a brief transient and is not used in MD calculations — MD is concerned with sustained loads. The motor overload relay is set at 100-112% of FLA per AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1. Option B — starting current is not used in MD. Option C — no such 80% factor exists for motors. Option D — motors are significant sustained loads and must be included.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 4.2; AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1"},
  {"id":"tp-048","topic":"Protection & Discrimination","sub_topic":"RCD cascade discrimination","difficulty":"hard","question":"A main 300mA Type S RCD at the main switchboard and a 30mA RCD at a distribution board installed in series achieves:","options":["Back-up protection — the 300mA RCD provides discrimination and fire protection while 30mA RCD provides personal protection at circuit level","Full discrimination so only the downstream RCD ever trips","An incorrect arrangement causing both to trip simultaneously on any fault","300mA and 30mA RCDs cannot be installed in series"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — A 300mA Type S (time-delayed) RCD at the origin provides discrimination against nuisance tripping of downstream 30mA RCDs, and fire protection (300mA can detect significant earth leakage that could cause heating/fire but is not sensitive enough for personal protection). The 30mA RCD at the distribution board provides personal protection for downstream circuits. This cascade arrangement is specifically recognised in AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.6.2. Option B is wrong — the 300mA main will trip on high earth leakage faults. Option C is wrong — this is a correct, standard arrangement. Option D is false — series RCDs are common and correct.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.6.2; AS/NZS 61009.1"},
  {"id":"tp-049","topic":"Protection & Discrimination","sub_topic":"MCB characteristic selection","difficulty":"hard","question":"Type C MCBs are specifically recommended for circuits supplying:","options":["Moderate inrush loads such as fluorescent lighting with magnetic ballasts, HID lamps, and small motor loads","Domestic lighting circuits with only filament lamps (purely resistive)","Stove and oven circuits","Long heavily loaded cable runs"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Type C MCBs have magnetic trip at 5-10× nominal current. They are suitable for circuits with moderate inrush: fluorescent lighting (magnetic ballasts), HID lamps, small motors. The inrush of these loads (typically 2-4× FLA for fluorescent, 5-10× for motors) would cause nuisance tripping of Type B (3-5× In) devices. Type D (10-20× In) is for very high inrush loads (transformers, large motors). Option B — filament lamps are purely resistive with minimal inrush; Type B is appropriate. Option C — stoves/ovens are resistive; Type B or C depending on electronic controls. Option D — MCB type selection is based on load inrush, not cable length.","reference":"AS/NZS 60898.1; AS/NZS 3000"},
  {"id":"tp-050","topic":"Protection & Discrimination","sub_topic":"RCD socket outlet rating","difficulty":"medium","question":"AS/NZS 3000 requires RCD protection for socket outlets rated at:","options":["20A and below — all standard socket outlets in any installation type (domestic, commercial, industrial)","32A and above only","10A only — standard household sockets","63A and above"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.6.2 requires RCD protection for all socket outlets rated not exceeding 20A. This covers 10A, 15A, and 20A socket outlets in ALL installation types. This is a core safety requirement because socket outlets supply portable equipment that may be handled during a fault. Option B is wrong — the 20A limit is the upper threshold, not the lower one. Option C is wrong — 15A and 20A outlets would be excluded, creating a significant safety gap. Option D is entirely wrong.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.6.2"},
  {"id":"tp-051","topic":"Protection & Discrimination","sub_topic":"RCBO advantage","difficulty":"medium","question":"An RCBO (Residual Current Breaker with Overload) provides a key advantage over a common RCD protecting multiple circuits:","options":["A fault on one circuit trips only that RCBO — other circuits on the same board remain energised","RCBOs are significantly cheaper than separate RCD+MCB combinations","RCBOs eliminate the need for coordination with upstream devices","RCBOs can be used as main isolating switches"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The main advantage of individual RCBOs per circuit is circuit-level discrimination: a fault on one circuit trips only that RCBO; other circuits on the same distribution board remain energised. With a common RCD protecting 4 circuits, any earth fault on any circuit trips the common RCD, blacking out all 4. Option B is false — RCBOs are more expensive than separate RCD + MCB. Option C is false — coordination is still required. Option D — RCBOs are protective devices; their use as switches depends on specific marking per the standard.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.6.2; AS/NZS 61009.1"},
  {"id":"tp-052","topic":"Supply Systems","sub_topic":"TN-S system","difficulty":"medium","question":"In a TN-S supply system, the neutral and earth conductors are:","options":["Separate throughout — dedicated PE conductor runs from the transformer alongside the separate neutral conductor","Combined as PEN from transformer to installation","Only earthed at the transformer, never at the installation","Connected together at every distribution point"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — TN-S (Separate Neutral and Earth) has a dedicated protective earth (PE) conductor running from the transformer alongside the line and neutral conductors. The earth is established at the transformer and connected to PE. At the installation, the PE connects to the MET. This differs from TN-C-S where PEN is combined from the transformer to the point of supply. Option B describes TN-C or TN-C-S. Option C is wrong — the installation's MEN link establishes a second earth connection. Option D is wrong — N and PE are connected only at specific points.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2.1; NZECP 34"},
  {"id":"tp-053","topic":"Supply Systems","sub_topic":"MEN link purpose","difficulty":"medium","question":"The primary purpose of the Multiple Earthed Neutral (MEN) link in a TN-C-S installation is to:","options":["Create a low-impedance fault return path to the supply transformer and establish the installation's earthed exposed parts at reference potential","Completely isolate the installation earth from the supply neutral","Provide a neutral return path for unbalanced loads only","Allow the main switch to be replaced without disrupting the earth path"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The MEN link connects the neutral bar to the earth bar at the main switchboard (MET). Its purposes: (1) provides a low-impedance fault current return path — without it, a line-to-earth fault cannot flow; (2) establishes exposed conductive parts at a reference potential relative to the supply neutral. Option B is wrong — the MEN link connects N and PE, not isolates them. Option C is incomplete — fault return is the primary purpose. Option D is not a purpose of the MEN link.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2.1; NZECP 34"},
  {"id":"tp-054","topic":"Supply Systems","sub_topic":"IT system","difficulty":"medium","question":"An IT (Impedance Earthed) supply system is characterised by:","options":["The supply neutral is earthed through a high impedance, limiting fault current and allowing continued operation on first earth fault with an alarm","The installation's earth electrode is connected directly to the MEN link without impedance","First earth fault is cleared by an RCD only","IT is the standard system for all NZ domestic installations"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — IT systems have the supply neutral either isolated (solidly IT) or connected through high impedance. The high impedance limits earth fault current, allowing the system to continue operating on a first fault (with an alarm) rather than automatically disconnecting. Used in hospitals (theatres), mines, and critical industrial facilities. Option B describes TT or TN. Option C is wrong — standard RCDs may not operate correctly on IT systems. Option D is wrong — MEN (TN-C-S) is standard in NZ.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2.3; NZECP 34"},
  {"id":"tp-055","topic":"Supply Systems","sub_topic":"Earth electrode resistance TT","difficulty":"hard","question":"The resistance of a TT system earth electrode (Ra) should be:","options":["Low enough that Ze + Ra results in Zs within Table 5.1 limits for the protective device protecting the circuit","At least 500Ω to limit touch voltage","Equal to the supply authority's declared Ze value","Ra is irrelevant in TT — only the supply electrode matters"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — In TT, the consumer installs a dedicated earth electrode (Ra) independent of the supply. The fault path is: line → earth electrode at fault → soil → consumer electrode (Ra) → soil → supply electrode → supply neutral. Zs = Ze + Ra. Ra must be low enough that Zs is within AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1 limits. There is no fixed minimum or maximum for Ra — it is determined by the required Zs. Option B (500Ω) would be far too high for most circuit Zs requirements. Option C — Ra is independent of Ze in TT. Option D is wrong — Ra is critical in TT.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 5.2.2; NZECP 34"},
  {"id":"tp-056","topic":"Motors & Motor Starters","sub_topic":"Star-delta starting","difficulty":"hard","question":"In a star-delta motor starter, during the starting (star) configuration, the motor winding voltage is:","options":["V/√3 (≈58%) of line voltage, reducing starting torque to approximately 33% of DOL torque","Equal to line voltage — star configuration has no voltage reduction effect","V/2 — half the line voltage","The same as delta but current is halved only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — In star, each winding is connected between a line and the star point. Winding voltage = Vline/√3 ≈ 0.577V. Since torque ∝ V², torque in star = (V/√3)² = V²/3 ≈ 33% of DOL torque. Starting current also reduces to 1/√3 ≈ 33% of DOL current. When near-rated speed, the starter switches to delta, applying full line voltage. Option B is false. Option C — V/2 is not the star winding voltage. Option D is wrong because winding voltage IS reduced in star.","reference":"AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1; motor starting theory"},
  {"id":"tp-057","topic":"Motors & Motor Starters","sub_topic":"Soft starter","difficulty":"hard","question":"A soft starter reduces motor starting current by:","options":["Gradually ramping up voltage applied to the motor windings using thyristors/SCRs, limiting inrush current to 2-3× FLA vs 5-7× for DOL","Inserting resistors in series with the motor throughout the starting sequence","Reducing the supply frequency below 50Hz during start-up","Using a reduced-voltage autotransformer with multiple fixed taps"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Soft starters use thyristors (SCRs) to phase-control the voltage applied to the motor. By gradually ramping voltage from a low initial value, the soft starter limits inrush current to typically 2-3× FLA (vs 5-7× for DOL). Soft starters also provide smooth torque ramp. Option B describes resistor starting, a different method. Option C describes a VFD function. Option D describes autotransformer starting, another different method.","reference":"AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1"},
  {"id":"tp-058","topic":"Motors & Motor Starters","sub_topic":"Motor overload setting","difficulty":"medium","question":"A 15kW three-phase motor has nameplate FLC of 28A. The thermal overload relay should be set at:","options":["28A × 100-112% = 28-31A — set to the motor's nameplate full load current per AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1","28A × 150% = 42A to allow for starting conditions","28A × 80% = 22A as a conservative setting","The overload setting depends on the cable size, not the motor rating"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1: thermal overload relays set to 100-112% of motor nameplate FLC. The overload is designed to carry the motor's rated current continuously without tripping. Option B (150%) would leave the motor unprotected against sustained overloads. Option C (80%) would cause nuisance tripping at normal full-load current. Option D is wrong — overload settings are based on motor FLC, not cable size.","reference":"AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1"},
  {"id":"tp-059","topic":"Motors & Motor Starters","sub_topic":"Motor starting current","difficulty":"medium","question":"A Direct On Line (DOL) started 7.5kW motor draws approximately how many times its full load current during starting?","options":["5-7× FLA — DOL starting produces high inrush current due to low rotor impedance at standstill","1-2× FLA — motors start smoothly without significant current increase","10-12× FLA — maximum current at start","Equal to FLC — DOL has no current increase at start"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — At standstill, the rotor has no back-EMF, so the stator draws very high magnetising current. Locked rotor current (LRA) for a DOL-started induction motor is typically 5-7× FLA. This causes voltage dip and must be considered in supply design. For star-delta, starting current reduces to 1/√3 ≈ 33% of DOL starting current. Option B is false. Option C (10-12×) is more typical of large special-purpose motors; 5-7× is the standard range. Option D is false.","reference":"AS/NZS IEC 60947-4-1; motor starting theory"},
  {"id":"tp-060","topic":"Motors & Motor Starters","sub_topic":"Motor isolation requirements","difficulty":"medium","question":"A motor circuit isolator must be:","options":["Capable of breaking full load current of the motor, located within sight of the motor or lockable in OFF position","Rated only for the control circuit current (typically 10A or less)","A simple pull-cord switch mounted on the motor","The building main switch is sufficient isolation for any motor circuit"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.9 and AS/NZS IEC 60204-1: motor isolators must break full load current and be within sight of the motor OR lockable in OFF position (so the motor cannot be started during maintenance). Option B is wrong — the isolator must break motor full load current, not just control circuit current. Option C is not a recognised motor isolation means. Option D is wrong — the building main switch may not be in sight of the motor and a non-lockable switch doesn't satisfy the lockable/off-sight requirement.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.9; AS/NZS IEC 60204-1"},
  {"id":"tp-061","topic":"Switchboards","sub_topic":"Busbar rating","difficulty":"hard","question":"A switchboard busbar protected by a 400A main circuit breaker must be rated at:","options":["At least 400A — equal to or greater than the rating of the protective device protecting it","150A less than the main circuit breaker rating","The sum of all outgoing circuit protective device ratings","Busbar rating is not specified in AS/NZS 3000"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 61439.1 requires busbars to be rated at least equal to the protective device protecting them. The busbar must carry the full fault current without damage. A 400A busbar protected by a 400A breaker is at its limit but compliant. Option B is not a standard rule. Option C — busbar rating is based on the upstream protective device, not the sum of downstream devices. Option D is false — AS/NZS 61439 specifies busbar rating requirements.","reference":"AS/NZS 61439.1; AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.8"},
  {"id":"tp-062","topic":"Switchboards","sub_topic":"Segregation requirements","difficulty":"medium","question":"Segregation of circuits within a switchboard is required to:","options":["Prevent a fault on one circuit propagating to adjacent circuits and prevent operators contacting live parts of other circuits during fault finding","Allow multiple circuits to share the same enclosure without any barrier","Reduce switchboard construction cost","Only required for circuits above 100A"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 61439.1 requires segregation (form separation) of circuits using barriers/partitions. Purposes: (1) operator safety — prevents contact with live parts of adjacent circuits during fault finding; (2) fault containment — prevents arc faults spreading to adjacent circuits; (3) reliability — prevents a fault on one circuit causing unintended operation of adjacent protective devices. Option B is the opposite of segregation requirements. Option C is wrong — segregation adds cost but is mandatory. Option D is wrong — requirements apply regardless of current rating.","reference":"AS/NZS 61439.1; AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.8"},
  {"id":"tp-063","topic":"Switchboards","sub_topic":"Working space","difficulty":"medium","question":"AS/NZS 3000 requires that the working space in front of a switchboard:","options":["Be maintained clear at all times — minimum clear depth of 0.6m for boards up to 250A, increasing for higher ratings","Allow materials to be stored provided the door can open","Be shared with telephone and data equipment if space is limited","Only applies to industrial switchboards"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.8 and AS/NZS IEC 60204-1 require a clear working space in front of switchboards. Minimum depth is 0.6m for boards up to 250A. The space must be kept clear — storage is prohibited. Option B is wrong. Option C — telephone/data equipment may not encroack on switchboard working space. Option D is wrong — requirements apply to all switchboards.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.8; AS/NZS IEC 60204-1"},
  {"id":"tp-064","topic":"Switchboards","sub_topic":"Circuit chart requirements","difficulty":"medium","question":"A switchboard circuit chart must show:","options":["The type and rating of each protective device and the circuit it supplies, kept up to date reflecting current configuration","Only the main switch rating","The owner's name and contact details","A schematic of the supply authority network"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 2.8 and Electricity (Safety) Regulations require a circuit chart or legend identifying each circuit, its protective device type and rating, and what it supplies. The chart must be kept current — changes to the installation must be reflected in an updated chart. Option B is insufficient. Option C is not required by AS/NZS 3000. Option D is not required.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 2.8"},
  {"id":"tp-065","topic":"Circuit Design","sub_topic":"Ring final circuit purpose","difficulty":"medium","question":"A ring final circuit (RFC) in a domestic installation serves primarily to:","options":["Provide two parallel current paths to each socket outlet, reducing voltage drop and providing redundancy if one path is broken","Reduce the total cable required compared to a radial circuit","Increase the fault level at each socket outlet","Allow socket outlets to be added without recalculating demand"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The RFC runs as a complete loop from the distribution board and back. Each socket has two current paths. Key advantages: (1) reduced voltage drop — current splits between two paths, halving the current in each cable segment; (2) redundancy — if cable is damaged at one point (not both paths), all outlets remain energised via the alternate route. Option B — RFC doesn't necessarily reduce total cable length; it allows smaller conductors due to current splitting. Option C is wrong. Option D is wrong — additions still require demand recalculation.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 4.2"},
  {"id":"tp-066","topic":"Circuit Design","sub_topic":"Protective conductor sizing","difficulty":"hard","question":"A 32A circuit protected by an MCB uses 6mm² active conductors. Per AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1, the minimum protective conductor (CPC) size is:","options":["6mm² — the CPC must be at least equal to the active size for this circuit rating","2.5mm² — protective conductors are typically smaller than actives","10mm² — protective conductors must be one size larger","1.5mm² — the minimum for any fixed installation protective conductor"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Table 5.1 specifies minimum CPC sizes. For a 32A circuit with 6mm² actives, the minimum CPC is typically 6mm² (equal to the active) for many installation methods. The CPC must be capable of carrying the fault current without overheating and without opening before the protective device clears the fault. For certain conditions the CPC may be calculated smaller, but for a standard 32A circuit with 6mm² actives, 6mm² is the minimum. Option B (2.5mm²) might be acceptable for smaller circuit sizes under specific conditions. Option D (1.5mm²) is too small for a 32A circuit. Option C is not a standard rule.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Table 5.1; AS/NZS 3008"},
  {"id":"tp-067","topic":"Circuit Design","sub_topic":"Sub-main sizing","difficulty":"hard","question":"A sub-main cable feeding a distribution board with multiple different-rated outgoing circuits should be sized for:","options":["The maximum demand of the distribution board calculated per AS/NZS 3000 Clause 4.2 diversity factors","The sum of all outgoing protective device ratings without diversity","The largest single outgoing protective device rating","The sub-main does not need separate sizing if the main is correctly sized"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Sub-mains are sized for the maximum demand of the load they serve, calculated using AS/NZS 3000 Clause 4.2 diversity factors applied to groups of circuits served. Summing all protective device ratings without diversity would significantly oversize the sub-main. Table 4.2 diversity factors reflect the fact that not all circuits operate at full load simultaneously. Option B is the common over-sizing error. Option C would potentially undersize. Option D is wrong — sub-mains must be individually assessed.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 4.2"},
  {"id":"tp-068","topic":"Circuit Design","sub_topic":"Neutral conductor sizing TN-C-S","difficulty":"hard","question":"In a TN-C-S installation, the neutral conductor in a sub-main circuit should:","options":["Be of the same current-carrying capacity as the active and be capable of being disconnected simultaneously with the active","Be half the size of the active conductor to save cost","Not be required — three-core cable with earth is sufficient","Be sized only for the unbalanced current only"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — In TN-C-S (MEN), the neutral carries the unbalanced current. It must be sized for the circuit's maximum demand — not automatically half the active size. For circuits with significant third harmonic content (common with switch-mode power supplies, LED drivers), the neutral current can exceed phase current due to harmonic triplen components, requiring the neutral to be sized accordingly or the circuit designed to handle it. The neutral must be disconnectible with the phase where required. Option B is wrong. Option C is wrong — neutral is always required. Option D is incomplete — neutral must carry the maximum demand current including harmonics.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 3.3; AS/NZS 3008"},
  {"id":"tp-069","topic":"Testing & Verification","sub_topic":"Earth continuity resistance","difficulty":"hard","question":"When testing earth continuity, the resistance measured should be:","options":["Low enough that Vtouch = Ifault × Rearth does not exceed 50V AC — the limit depends on the protective device and fault current","Less than 1Ω regardless of circuit length","Equal to the phase conductor resistance","Tested only at the main earthing conductor"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Earth continuity test ensures the protective conductor can carry fault current without producing dangerous touch voltages. The criterion is: Vtouch = Ifault × Rearth < 50V. Since Ifault for a 32A MCB on a dead-short is ~160A, Rearth must be < 50V/160A = 0.31Ω. AS/NZS 3000/3019 provide maximum earth conductor resistances per circuit/protective device. Option B (1Ω) is a rule of thumb but not the formal test criterion — for a 32A circuit the limit is ~0.3Ω. Option C is not the test basis. Option D is wrong — each circuit's earth continuity must be tested.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 8.3.3; AS/NZS 3019"},
  {"id":"tp-070","topic":"Testing & Verification","sub_topic":"Polarity testing","difficulty":"medium","question":"Polarity testing of a single-phase circuit confirms that:","options":["Every switch, including the main switch, breaks the active (line) conductor only — not the neutral","The neutral and earth are correctly identified","All three phases are correctly sequenced in a three-phase circuit","The circuit is connected to the correct phase of the supply"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — AS/NZS 3000 Clause 8.3.6: polarity testing confirms that every switching device (including the main switch and all single-pole switches) breaks the LINE conductor only. If a switch breaks neutral, the circuit remains live even when switched off — a serious shock hazard. Option B is an identification/continuity check. Option C is phase sequence testing. Option D is a supply connection check, not the primary purpose of polarity testing per the standard.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 8.3.6"},
  {"id":"tp-071","topic":"Testing & Verification","sub_topic":"RCD test button","difficulty":"medium","question":"The test button on an RCD operates by:","options":["Injecting a calibrated fault current (typically 30mA for a 30mA RCD) through the RCD's internal test circuit to simulate earth leakage, causing it to trip","Forcing the RCD contacts to weld together to check mechanical operation","Measuring the earth electrode resistance by injecting a small current","Disabling the RCD's electronic circuit to verify mechanical trip"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — The RCD test button applies a calibrated resistance across line and earth terminals inside the RCD, injecting a simulated earth leakage current equal to the RCD's rated trip current (e.g., 30mA for a 30mA RCD). If the RCD trips, the test circuit and trip mechanism are confirmed functional. IMPORTANT: the test button only tests the internal test circuit — it does NOT test the RCD's ability to trip on real external earth leakage. A full functional test with an earth leakage tester is required for comprehensive RCD testing. Option B is wrong. Option C is what an earth electrode tester does. Option D is wrong.","reference":"AS/NZS 3000:2018 Clause 8.3.8"},
  {"id":"tp-072","topic":"Testing & Verification","sub_topic":"Test instrument calibration","difficulty":"medium","question":"Insulation resistance and earth fault loop impedance testers used for compliance testing must be:","options":["Calibrated with a valid test record — instrument accuracy directly affects whether compliant results are measured or borderline results missed","New (purchased within 12 months) to ensure accuracy","Supplied or approved by the supply authority","Self-checking instruments that do not require calibration"],"correct_answer":0,"explanation":"CORRECT — Test instrument accuracy directly affects compliance outcomes. An out-of-calibration insulation tester could miss a genuine 0.8 MΩ failure or fail a genuinely compliant 1.2 MΩ installation. AS/NZS 3019 requires test instruments to be calibrated and maintained. Calibration certificates should be current (typically 12-24 months). Option B is false — age is not the criterion; calibration status is. Option C is false. Option D is false — no test instrument is self-calibrating.","reference":"AS/NZS 3019; instrument calibration requirements"},
]

